{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c7c1b2c1-5a91-4f0b-bbf0-abe18998883d","content":"Your project uses **Microsoft.Testing.Platform** (via `global.json`). It has built-in hang detection. Just run:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --hang-dump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nThe `--` separates `dotnet test` arguments from the testing platform arguments. If a test hangs for over 5 minutes, the runner will terminate it, produce a dump, and report which test was stuck.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"927d8972-fee6-43fa-9850-9e5afc70ed8b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is an MSTest project using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (the new test runner). To add a 5-minute hang timeout, I need to configure the `--hang-dump-timeout` option or use a `.runsettings` file.\n\nSince they're using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as indicated by the `global.json` test runner setting), the hang detection is configured via command-line options:\n\n```\ndotnet test --hang-dump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nOr they can configure it in the project file or a `.testconfig` file.\n\nActually, with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can pass `--hang-dump-timeout` directly:\n\n\nThe simplest approach is to run `dotnet test -- --hang-dump-timeout 5m`, which will automatically enable hang detection and dump diagnostics if the tests hang for longer than 5 minutes. They could also add this to their project configuration via `<TestingPlatformCommandLineArguments>` if they want it to persist across runs.","outputTokens":443},"id":"52ebbca4-fd73-4ba3-8a68-2f1ca383fb80","timestamp":"2026-04-07T14:21:00.164Z","parentId":"93e9ce38-daea-43c3-8cf3-c95649d53b8f"}
